\begin{abstract}
Prime numbers are one of the most important concepts in mathematics, especially because of their role in cryptography and computational systems. In this project, three prime generation algorithms were compared: Basic Trial Division, Optimized Trial Division, and the Sieve of Eratosthenes. All algorithms were implemented in Python and benchmarked across increasing input sizes. The results demonstrate that algorithmic design has a major impact on performance. While optimized trial division significantly improved upon the basic approach, the Sieve of Eratosthenes consistently produced the fastest runtimes and remained practical even for input sizes up to ten million.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Prime numbers are integers greater than 1 that are divisible only by 1 and themselves. They play an important role in number theory, cryptography, and computer science.

This project investigates the following question:

\begin{quote}
How does algorithm choice affect the efficiency of prime number generation as input size increases?
\end{quote}

To answer this question, three different algorithms were implemented and tested using Python.

\section{Algorithms}

\subsection{Basic Trial Division}

Basic trial division checks every possible divisor from 2 to $n-1$. Although simple, it performs many unnecessary checks and becomes inefficient for large values of $n$.

\subsection{Optimized Trial Division}

A mathematical observation allows trial division to be improved. If a number has a factor, at least one factor must be less than or equal to $\sqrt{n}$. Therefore only divisors up to $\sqrt{n}$ need to be checked.

\subsection{Sieve of Eratosthenes}

The Sieve of Eratosthenes generates all primes up to a given limit by systematically eliminating multiples of known primes. Instead of testing each number individually, it removes composite numbers from consideration.

\section{Methodology}

All algorithms were implemented in Python. Runtime measurements were recorded using \texttt{time.perf\_counter()}.

Input sizes tested included:

\begin{itemize}
\item 1,000
\item 10,000
\item 100,000
\item 1,000,000
\end{itemize}

Additional tests were conducted for the Sieve of Eratosthenes at:

\begin{itemize}
\item 2,000,000
\item 5,000,000
\item 10,000,000
\end{itemize}

