\section{Discussion}

The results demonstrate that algorithm choice has a significant effect on computational performance.

Basic trial division became impractical as the input size increased. At $N=100,000$, the runtime exceeded 35 seconds. The optimized trial division algorithm significantly reduced runtime by limiting divisor checks to $\sqrt{n}$.

The Sieve of Eratosthenes consistently outperformed both trial division methods. The performance gap widened as the input size increased, indicating superior scalability.

The graphs visually confirm these findings and show that the sieve remained practical even when generating all primes up to ten million.

\section{Conclusion}

This project compared three methods for generating prime numbers: Basic Trial Division, Optimized Trial Division, and the Sieve of Eratosthenes.

The results showed that:

\begin{itemize}
\item The square-root optimization dramatically improved trial division.
\item The Sieve of Eratosthenes was the fastest algorithm at every tested input size.
\item The performance advantage of the sieve increased as the input size grew.
\item Basic trial division became impractical for sufficiently large values of $N$.
\end{itemize}

Overall, the Sieve of Eratosthenes proved to be the most effective method for generating large collections of prime numbers.

